Gall (
Figs 54–56
). The gall is a swelling of branches and twigs, usually located in middle of twig, not apically; sometimes swellings at joints of twigs; up to 6.0 cm long, 1.2–1.5 cm in diameter, coloured the same as the bark of twigs. When the gall mature, tissues hard, lignified. Larval chambers (up to 14 mm in length and 3–5 mm in diameter) arranged perpendicularly to main axis of gall, radiating from center of twig toward gall surface, reaching to 2– 3 mm from surface (
Fig. 56
).

Distribution . Taiwan : currently known from Nantou County, Lienhuachih Forest Research Centre only (
Fig. 57
).
